{"cursor":"82784","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n in Karbala, Iraq is a holy site for Shia Muslims]]\n\n\n\n'Shia Islam' (, ShÄ«Ê¿ah) is the second largest denomination of Islam. Adherents\nof Shia Islam are called 'Shi'ites' or 'Shias'. \"Shia\" is the short form of the\nhistoric phrase ShÄ«Ê»atul Ê»AlÄ« (), meaning \"followers\", \"faction\", or \"party\" of\nMuhammad's son-in-law and cousin Ali, whom the Shia believe to be Muhammad's\nsuccessor in the Caliphate.\n\nLike other branches of Islam, Shia Islam is based on the teachings of the Quran\nand the message of the Islamic prophet Muhammad. \"Esposito, John. \"What Everyone Needs to Know about Islam.\" Oxford\nUniversity Press, 2002 | ISBN 978-0-19-515713-0. p. 40 In\ncontrast to other types, the Shia believe that only God has the right to choose\na representative to safeguard Islam, the Quran and [[sharia]]. Thus the Shias\nlook to Ali, Muhammad's son-in-law, whom they consider divinely appointed, as\nthe rightful successor to Muhammad, and the first imam. The Shia extend this\nbelief to Muhammad's family, the [[Ahl al-Bayt]] (\"the People of the House\"),\nand certain individuals among his descendants, known as [[The Twelve\nImams|imams]], who have special spiritual and political authority over the\ncommunity.\n\nAlthough there were many Shia branches throughout history, modern Shia Islam is\ndivided into three main branches. \"Esposito, John. \"What Everyone Needs to\nKnow about Islam\" Oxford University Press, 2002. ISBN 978-0-19-515713-0.\np.40 The largest Shia sect in the early 21st century is the\n[[Twelver|Ithna ashariyya]], commonly referred to\nin English as the Twelvers, while smaller branches include the Ismaili and Zaidi\n(\"Fivers\"). Tabataba'i (1979), p. 76 Alevis, Alawis and Druze are also\nconsidered sects of Shia Islam.\n","linknr":1596,"url":"Shi'a","recorded":1362669239,"links":129,"instances":["ismaili_doctrine","tribe","calendar_month","islam"],"pdf":["http://pewfo